      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Repair invoke-style plain-text tool calls",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Extend plain-text tool-call repair to recognize XML-ish invoke calls with named parameter arguments.\n- Keep streamed invoke-style tool-call text buffered so it can be promoted into structured tool-call events instead of leaking as assistant text.\n- Allow standalone text tool-call promotion when the terminal reason is `toolUse`, improving compatibility with models such as Opus 4.8 that may emit XML-ish tool-call text.\n- Preserve ordinary visible-text examples that contain `<invoke ...>` snippets, while keeping existing non-invoke XML repair behavior unchanged.\n\n## Behavior\nThis only affects malformed/plain-text tool-call repair paths. Normal structured tool calls continue to use the existing provider-native flow unchanged.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- behavior: Opus 4.8-style XML-ish plain-text tool-call output can be repaired into a structured tool-call event instead of being emitted as assistant text. Existing `length` fallback promotion and legacy XML scrub behavior are preserved, while ordinary visible prose examples that contain `<invoke ...>` remain visible.\n- environment: Redacted local OpenClaw gateway/wrapper setup running the OpenClaw provider stream compatibility path through Node. Hostnames, endpoints, local paths, and account details are omitted.\n- steps: Ran a local OpenClaw wrapper smoke command that feeds three after-fix inputs: an existing bracketed plain-text tool call ending with `length`, an XML-ish invoke plain-text tool call ending with `toolUse`, and visible prose containing an `<invoke ...>` example.\n- evidence:\n\n```text\nlength fallback: event types = [\"toolcall_start\", \"toolcall_delta\", \"done\"]\nlength fallback: done.reason = \"toolUse\"\nlength fallback: tool name = \"exec\"\nlength fallback: arguments = { \"command\": \"date\" }\n\ninvoke toolUse input:\ncall\n<invoke name=\"exec\">\n<parameter name=\"command\">date</parameter>\n</invoke>\n\ninvoke toolUse: event types = [\"toolcall_start\", \"toolcall_delta\", \"done\"]\ninvoke toolUse: done.reason = \"toolUse\"\ninvoke toolUse: tool name = \"exec\"\ninvoke toolUse: arguments = { \"command\": \"date\" }\n\nvisible-text regression input:\nExample:\\n<invoke name=\"Bash\">\\n<parameter name=\"command\">ls</parameter>\\n</invoke>\n\nvisible-text regression output:\nExample:\\n<invoke name=\"Bash\">\\n<parameter name=\"command\">ls</parameter>\\n</invoke>\n```\n\n- observedResult: Both compatibility tool-call paths produced structured tool-call content and emitted `toolcall_start`, `toolcall_delta`, and final `done` events. The visible prose example kept its `<invoke ...>` snippet instead of being stripped.\n- notTested: No live external model request is included in this proof; provider credentials and endpoints are intentionally omitted. Normal structured tool calls are unchanged by this path and were not re-proven here.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: Runtime output is redacted and uses a local OpenClaw wrapper smoke run so no private endpoint, account, gateway, session, host, IP address, or token is exposed.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): Current main lacks support for invoke-style XML-ish openings with named parameter tags in the plain-text tool-call parser, so the same shape can leak as assistant text instead of being promoted.\n\n## Tests and validation\n- `node node_modules/vitest/vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.unit-fast.config.ts src/agents/embedded-agent-utils.test.ts src/plugin-sdk/tool-payload.test.ts --reporter=verbose`\n- `node node_modules/vitest/vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.unit-fast.config.ts src/plugin-sdk/provider-stream-shared.test.ts --reporter=verbose`\n\n## Privacy\nNo personal hostnames, private endpoints, credentials, local paths, IP addresses, gateway ports, account details, or tokens are included in this PR.\r\n",
